%S A397063 7,15,24,35,47,60,75,90,107,124,142,161,180,201,222,244,266,289,313,
%T A397063 337,362,388,414,440,468,495,524,552,582,611,642,673,704,736,768,800,
%U A397063 833,867,901,935,970,1006,1041,1077,1114,1151,1188,1226,1264,1302,1341
%N A397063 a(n) is the smallest integer exceeding 2*Pi*sqrt(n*(n+1)*(2*n+1)/6).
%C A397063 Fiedler bifurcation thresholds for circulant social networks.
%C A397063 a(n) is the smallest integer exceeding 2*Pi*sqrt(n*(n+1)*(2*n+1)/6), which equals the smallest k such that the circulant graph C(k,{1,...,n}) has Fiedler value lambda_2 <= 1.
%C A397063 In the context of network topology, the algebraic connectivity (Fiedler value) of a graph measures its robustness and synchronization speed. This sequence gives the maximum size k-1 of a circulant network with jump size up to n before its connectivity drops below the threshold of 1.
%C A397063 Furthermore, eigenvalues of such highly symmetric graphs find applications in chemical graph theory, particularly in evaluating the stability and energy levels of cyclic and bridged molecular structures (Cvetkovic, 1980).
%C A397063 In the context of social network analysis, this sequence can serve as a theoretical model for group cohesion thresholds (related to Dunbar's numbers). If n represents an individual's cognitive capacity to maintain mutual ties, then a(n)-1 is the maximum community size k that can be formed before the network's algebraic connectivity drops below 1, causing the group to lose structural cohesion and become vulnerable to fragmentation.
%C A397063 The exponent 3/2 in the asymptotic formula a(n) ~ (2*Pi/sqrt(3))*n^(3/2) agrees with the scaling exponent independently derived by West et al. (2020) from a dynamical complexity model of social networks.
%D A397063 D. Cvetkovic, M. Doob and H. Sachs, Spectra of Graphs: Theory and Applications, Academic Press, New York, 1980.
%H A397063 R. I. M. Dunbar, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/0047-2484(92)90081-J">Neocortex size as a constraint on group size in primates</a>, J. Human Evolution, 22 (1992), 469-493.
%H A397063 M. Fiedler, <a href="https://dml.cz/handle/10338.dmlcz/101168">Algebraic connectivity of graphs</a>, Czechoslovak Mathematical Journal, 23 (1973), 298-305.
%H A397063 B. J. West et al., <a href="https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.2006875117">Relating size and functionality in human social networks through complexity</a>, PNAS, 117 (2020), 18355-18358.
%F A397063 a(n) = ceiling(2*Pi*sqrt(n*(n+1)*(2*n+1)/6)).
%F A397063 a(n) = ceiling(2*Pi*sqrt(A000330(n))).
%F A397063 a(n) ~ (2*Pi/sqrt(3)) * n^(3/2) as n -> infinity.
%F A397063 More precisely: a(n) ~ (2*Pi/sqrt(3)) * n^(3/2) * (1 + 3/(4*n) + O(1/n^2)).
%t A397063 Table[Ceiling[2*Pi*Sqrt[n*(n+1)*(2*n+1)/6]], {n, 1, 51}]
%Y A397063 Cf. A000330, A000292.
